Inflation in Europe has taken over food
Rapid inflation, measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid increase in food prices.
In November, the increase in prices in the 13 euro area countries was higher than the forecast, after an inflation rate of 2.6 per cent in October, an annual inflation of 3.1 per cent was recorded, the European Community statistics office in Luxembourg reported.
Official forecasts indicated only 3 per cent, Bloomberg reported.
Contrary to the US, British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the rate of direct interest by saying that lower interest rates, with higher commodity prices and lower unemployment, would lead to the generation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to maintain the inflation rate below but close to two percent.
According to one analyst, it is Catch 22 for the ECB that "inflation must be deterred" so as not to have to intervene on this subject later.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 per cent is a record in the last 12 years and in Spain, it is increased from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the euro area has taken off because of the rapid increase in food and energy prices.
Cereal market shares have increased by 88 per cent and the soybean price has also reached its highest value since 1973.
The price of food oil and dairy products also increased considerably in 2007.
This year, the world oil price rose by 52 per cent and last month, a black gold barrel cost almost $100.
According to the ECB, in 2008, the inflation rate will fall from 2.1 this year to 2.5 per cent, but in 2009, it will fall to 1.9.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3 percent, however, the next 3-4 months, the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to decrease the Governing Rate twice in 2008.
