Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has increased its prices by almost twenty percent
Hypermarkets in Budaörs' commercial triangle maintained an average price increase of 16% last year compared with the fact that this year the VAT rate has not increased.
Article of Napi Gazdaság (Day Economy)
This year, in the trade triangle of Budaörs, the usual daily Christmas basket also increased by 16 percent on average, an increase of significantly higher than a thousand forts in all hypermarkets.
The prices, 'which had already flown' in the large food stores last December, did not increase sharply compared to the previous high base.
However, consumers are, of course, shocked to see that the items purchased clearly below nine thousand forks last year now cost more than ten thousand forks.
The daily basket in the surveyed hypermarkets exceeded at least 91 forints, the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints.
And the highest value in the basket was 10 573 forints.
(In 2003, this value was 6 800 forints.)
The prices of Unicum and live fish remained almost at last year's level, but the prices of turkey net, nuts and peacocks have increased considerably.
In stores, the price of flour and bread followed the data of the KSH (Central Institute of Statistics) but, at Auchan, we found bread from one kilo to only 139 forints.
Competition has not lowered the price of the product below 200 forints.
It was surprising to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the bottle contained in two liters of Coca-Cola was below 200 forints, so it cost only 257 forints the bottle included.
This year, in terms of daily shopping, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora was the cheapest.
According to our calculations, Cora increased its daily basket price by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan increased them by about 18 and 18 percent respectively.
By comparing the cheapest basket of last year and the cheapest basket of this year, we find a difference of 12 percent while the difference between the lowest basket of last year and the most expensive basket of this year is 21 percent.
Prices increased by an average of 1,480.
Last year, prices increased by an average of 1,206, while knowing that the impact of the increase in the VAT rate had already been noted in last year's Christmas prices.
This process caused trade to be perplexed, and hypermarkets could not visibly determine what margin to apply on products so far they were unable to predict the impact of price change on consumption.
(If a merchant miscalculates the rotation of a product, he may lose a large profit on the margin adapted to the intensity of the trade.)
Due to the change in VAT rate, the increase in daily basket prices has evolved so excessively that the most expensive basket was higher than the value of the 2006 basket, while the difference between the least expensive baskets was only 844.
This year, the difference was not so excessive as the value of the basket was higher than that of last year and the prices at least increased by 1,284 forints as well.
By approaching the two Christmas seasons, we found a catastrophic increase in prices, in less than 20 months the prices of daily consumption items increased by more than 30 percent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm KSH data: for some essential foods, the Institute of Statistics has seen an increase in prices by more than 30 per cent in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, with flour and egg.)
According to the daily Cartier of the latter, this seems almost absurd because the price level of this product, already quite expensive last year, has just increased by just over 10 per cent compared to the base.
According to the indices, flour suppliers occupy a higher position than egg suppliers because they have succeeded in making the brutal price increase accepted by multinationals as well.
In the commercial gold triangle, hypermarkets do not complain, they constantly record good years.
According to our experiences, the majority of customers no longer look at prices in the three hypermarkets visited.
They buy everything in quantity, they take long-containing food by pallets.
On Wednesday morning, important tails formed in the boxes of the three hypermarkets as the number of customers increased sharply.
However, according to our information, turnover is less important in the province, many multinationals complain to survey companies not even reach the expected turnover, not only for food but also for sustainable consumer items.
Many hospitals save on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, mainly caused by the incorrect use of antibiotics, have been recorded in hospitals.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the insufficient number of beds, the overuse of medical personnel do not help block infections, says the chief doctor at the National Epidemiology Centre.
Many hospitals also make the economy on disinfectants
Recently, MRSA infection was diagnosed with trauma at János Hospital.
The antibiotic-resistant bacteria were detected on a hospitalized man following a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The injured person from a serious car accident left the hospital but soon after he had to return there because of an MRSA infection and since then doctors have not been able to perform an important operation because of the bacteria in his body.
Until 10 December of this year, 1,094 hospital infections generated by a multi-resistant pathogen were reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, chief physician of the National Epidemiology Centre.
That is the number of infections caused by a multi-resistant pathogen that has actually been registered in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
Approximately two-thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, i.e. by methicillin-oxacilline-resistant gold staphylococcus.
One third of the people are carriers of the bacteria Staphylococcus aureus (SA) in their noses without developing a disease.
Infections caused by SAs (such as anginas, amygdalitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) react well to antibiotics, they are easily healing.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacteria, which responds well to antibiotics, will develop a bacteria that is well resistant to antibiotics that will rapidly proliferate in poor hospital conditions.
In the event of temporary or prolonged functioning of the immune system, this bacteria may cause serious hospital infections, such as traumatic infection or septicaemia, on the elderly, low weight or weakened organism.
According to the hospital director János, there is nothing special about MRSA infections, these infections are part of the daily routine of hospitals.
Above all, one should not confuse infection with the epidemic, one cannot find MRSA only the one or not looking for them, said Tibor Nyulasi.
SAs are resistant to antibiotics.
"These patients are isolated, the caretakers put gloves in rubber and protective masks and we have antibiotics suitable to cure them," Tibor Nyulasi said.
A priori, hospitalized patients are examined if they are carriers of MRSA, but infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling is not in mode
While the vast majority of MRSA infections may be prevented, current conditions and circumstances are not favourable in Hungarian hospitals to prevent the development and proliferation of multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and elderly homes, hospitals should control hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients carrying MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not in fashion in Hungarian hospitals.
It is important to know that the National Social Security Fund does not finance these reviews.
Most cases can only be seen if the MSSA infection is detectable on the patient, said the chief doctor at the epidemiological center.
The European Union has strong recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also Hungarian guidelines for the healing of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts should be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, i.e. microbiological examinations should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take this into account.
The realization of microbiological sampling is even more rare in outpatient care and basic care, Karolina Böröcz reported.
Many hospitals save on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSAs proliferate from one patient to another most often through medical personnel.
It is therefore essential to wash your hands, put gloves and masks of protection. However, important gaps are also detected in hospitals in this area.
MRSAs proliferate by inhalation of droplets and by contact. However, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, contaminated patients may not always be isolated.
In addition, the rooms are often full, the beds are often too close to each other while in terms of epidemic, the patients should be kept away from each other at least 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately, we also see that hospitals, in difficult financial situations, make savings on disinfectants, they lack nurses, there are many patients, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina Böröcz.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals or preventive measures are respected, the number of infections is lower in a demonstrable way or the proliferation of the pathogen can be blocked.
Government project against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection represents exorbitant expenditures for social security funds, which is why we are fighting against this infection everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the impact of CIHR.
According to published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) highlights among its priorities the prevention of the incidence of multi-resistant pathogens (such as MRSAs) and the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
