Additional EUR 400 million for infrastructure
János Veres, Minister of Finance, and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed three agreements of a total value of EUR 400 million in Budapest on a credit line to support education, transport infrastructure and energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) adopted a budget of EUR 300 million for the Hungarian budget financing of transport and environmental projects to be carried out from the Cohesion Fund with a loan contract of EUR 100 million already signed by the parties. This time, the signed contract concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The EUR 150 million credit agreement also concerns the budgetary financing of education projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for Hungary and the remaining EUR 150 million will be used later following the extension of the credit agreement.
The parties have signed a EUR 50 million contract for innovation, the state budget will use this envelope first as part of the research and development project to be carried out at the University of Debrecen.
During the negotiations, the Metro Line 4 project was also discussed.
The parties agreed that they would reconsider the possible modification of the initial contract when Hungary completed the details of the metro financing with the EU.
According to János Veres, this could be done in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has granted a total of EUR 8.4 billion for the financing of 113 projects in Hungary.
The EIB shall grant its appropriations at the interest rate linked to EURIBOR, with a grace period of 8 years and without a commitment commission.
