The British army units report on the video sharing site records made during its operations in Iraq and Afghanistan with a view to becoming popular.
First, it was the British Air Force (RAF) who was passionate about YouTube: the special units involved in Afghanistan are responsible for video sequences on Taliban operations since March 2006, the BBC announced.
These recordings, taken using miniature cameras mounted on the helmet, are checked at the headquarters of the air force operations in Kandahar and are then transferred to Londres or the compatriots charge them on the Internet.
The political message is inevitable
Air Force soldiers have already spent 139 sequences on the net through this route and their "chain" has been watched by more than 75 thousand people.
The British Ministry of Defence entered under the name "defenceheadquarters" in spring 2007 and reported videos on operations in Iraq and Afghanistan while the Commonwealth Office (Commonwealth Office) and the international peacekeeping forces in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own YouTube channels.
Mission to Afghanistan
According to the initial target of the air force, the videos were passed over the net to recruit. According to the Ministry of Defence, they were also used to make known to the general public the actual objectives of the presence of the army abroad.
The propaganda published by this route costs practically nothing compared to the usual recruitment advertisements on television, to be communicated to BBC Gordon Mackenzie, a defence consultant, but it also inevitably carries a political message, since it justifies in a special form the well-founded military operations decided by the government.
The Americans played a game
