Political Capital: The Hungarian Guard has increased the risk country
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital (Risk Analysis Division), the activity of the Hungarian Guard, formed last August, with the support of Jobbik Magyarszágért Mozgalom (Movement for a Better Hungary) increases the political risk of Hungary and the region.
In its "risk warning", the company notes that, in relation to the activity of the Hungarian Guard, the greatest political risk is that "in the short term aggressive ethnic confrontations can occur as a result of the escalation of the already existing ethnic tension between the Gypsy and non-Tzigan population of Hungary."
The research institute has added that the Hungarian Guard's political strategy to likely provoke this situation is the main reason.
As they say, this is explained by one of the main shortcomings of the Hungarian political actors: "public actors have given public debate on the Roma case to representatives of radical and extreme political groupings that have based a political strategy on the dispute between the Gypsies and the Hungarians."
The problem is aggravated, normal dialogue becomes impossible, extremists are strengthened, and the arrival of aggressive conflicts is more likely, they say.
However, according to the research institute, under the increased attention of the Hungarian and international media, the activity of the Hungarian Guard "has significantly deteriorated the image of Hungary abroad, in particular on confidence in the stability and democratic maturity of the country."
They recall that, following greater publicity given to the reorganization of the Hungarian radical and extreme right groups since the fall of 2006, many associations have been established in Hungary since the summer of 2007 as "national self-defense association".
"The common feature of these gatherings is that they define themselves as a civil organization when they publicly declare the preparation of their members to defence missions (catastrophes, national defence, defence of order), armed if necessary, further, by referring to the inability of the police, the army, i.e. the state," they added.
They pointed out that everything was going on in accordance with the method that, based on the retaliation of the political society and parties, seeks to disguise different political ambitions in a civil way.
The emphasis on civil character and association status is therefore only used to avoid the legal traps of registration of these associations in the court but they are also a political strategy.
The analysis indicates that the activity of the Hungarian Guard is a factor that also increases the risk compared to neighbouring relationships.
"In recent months, many neighbouring countries have cited the Hungarian Guard as a source of potential risk and the ultra-nationalist political actors of some neighbouring countries want to justify their anti-Hungarian policy by referring to the constitution of the Hungarian Guard.
This influences the political stability of the region," they added.
