After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which depict the fate of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are free access.
The 47 million archival documents, stored on 27 km of line in Bad Arolsen, Hesse, were so far only available for a "humanitarian" purpose, i.e., individually and nominally, on request of a former victim or his entitled.
The eleven states in charge of their management - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
