Until recently, several States, including Germany, had opposed the opening of these nomination documents to the public because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
Like the alleged homosexuality or mental disability of certain victims of deportation.
Registers of concentration camps or arrest warrants established by the Gestapo had been gathered after war for a practical purpose: to find civilians deported or subject to compulsory work and, possibly, to give them proof of their internality, in order to open the way for their compensation.
Today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees deal with tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, for part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
