Venus is the infernal twin of the Earth.
Despite its hostile atmosphere of life, Venus is more like Earth than we thought so far: the European space probe "Venus Express" has discovered lightning in the atmosphere and wind turbines at poles, similar to those that appear in winter on Earth.
For almost three decades, scientists have assumed that there are lightnings on Venus.
The European "Venus Express" probe has now proved it - it has detected electromagnetic waves at the limit of the atmosphere: the lightnings on Venus explode at a height of about 56 kilometres of cloud cloud, reports Christopher Russel of the University of California in Los Angeles in the scientific magazine "Nature".
According to the famous theory of cyprine, the lightnings would have revealed life on Earth: the storm would have stimulated reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the cornerstone of life.
This is not the case with Venus: "If life had been there, it must have been at a very old date in history," explains Sean Solomon of the "Carnegie Institution" in Washington.
There should be few living things on Venus' surface today: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, sometimes there are temperatures of 500 degrees.
"Venus is perhaps the infernal twin of the Earth, but she remains a twin," Russel said.
Why Venus, which resembles so much the massive and dimensional Earth, has been struck by such a different evolution, is the fundamental question of the ASE mission.
The departure of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was an important step in Venezuelan research, since no more probes were on the way to exploring this planet since the 1990s.
In the opinion of researchers, the most recent research results that have now been presented in several "Nature" articles do not only highlight Venus' singularity within the solar system.
They also show that the common points with the Earth of our neighbouring planet are more than supposed at first glance.
Thus researchers found, in addition to the wind turbines already known at the north pole, a cloud peat at the south pole, which turns even faster.
The phenomenon recalls the air currents in the terrestrial hemispheres in winter, writes a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni of the Institute of Astrophysica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica Italian.
The second planet of the solar system has almost the same mass as the Earth and is, with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers, almost as large.
The planet qualified as a star in the evening or in the morning revolves around the sun in just 225 days.
However, it turns much more slowly on itself: one Venetian day lasts 243 earth days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, does not recall much the Earth, scientists assume that both planets have formed under similar conditions.
Of the two, the water accumulated and remained on Earth in the form of oceans, but lost in space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide has been fixed on Earth in the form of carbonate, it constitutes the largest part of the atmosphere on Venus.
